\begin{minipage}{10cm}
We assume to know (at least numerically) the unique solution of (1) and denote it by $\vec{x}$.
We then plug it into $\tens{A}(\vec{x}(t),t)$ and obtain the \textbf{linear} system of ordinary differential equations
\[
	\deriv{t}\,\vec{x}(t) = \tens{A}(t)\,\vec{x}(t)+\vec{u}(t),\quad t>t_0.
\]
This equation has the general solution formula
\vspace{-0.25cm}
\[
	\vec{x}(t) = \underbrace{\tens{\Phi}(t,t_0)\,\vec{x_0}}_{\text{age}(t)=t-t_0+\text{initial age}}
	+\intl_{t_0}^t 
	\underbrace{\tens{\Phi}(t,\tau)\,\vec{u}(\tau)}_{\text{age}(t)=t-\tau}\,d\tau,
\]
where $\tens{\Phi}$ is the so-called state transition matrix.
This leads immediately to the {\color{red}vector of age densities}
\[
	\vec{p}(a,t) = 
	\begin{cases}
		\tens{\Phi}(t,t_0)\,\vec{p_0}(a-(t-t_0)),\quad & a\geq t-t_0,\\
		\tens{\Phi}(t,t-a)\,\vec{u}(t-a),& a<t-t_0,
	\end{cases}
\]
where $\vec{p_0}$ is the initial age distribution.
\end{minipage}
